<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF108-666-222  </DOCNO><DOCID>08 666 222.andM;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Newsbytes  June 12 1990* Full Text COPYRIGHT Newsbytes Inc. 1990.andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Cocom rules relaxed for exports to Eastern Bloc countries.andO;(Coordinating Committee for Multilateral Export Controls)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Gold, Steve.andM;</AUTHOR><DESCRIPT>Topic:     Coordinating Committee for Multilateral Export ControlsEastern EuropeGovernment RegulationInternational TradeTechnology transfer.andM;</DESCRIPT><TEXT>COCOM RULES RELAXED FOR EXPORTS TO EASTERN BLOC COUNTRIES BONN, WEST GERMANY,1990 JUN 09 (NB) -- The member countries of Cocom, the technology body thatagrees what levels of technology may be legally exported to Eastern Europe,has agreed to considerably ease its list of restricted items.andM;Speaking in a special communique, West German Economics Minister HelmutHaussmann said that the easing of Cocom rules facilitate exports of machinetools, telecommunications installations and computers to countries belongingto the former communist bloc.andP;  In addition, virtually all restrictions onexports to East Germany will shortly be lifted, he added.andM;Haussmann said the meeting in Paris made five decisions, providing for:andM;[] Free access for East Germany to almost all Western technologyandM;[] An easing restrictions on exports of machine tools, telecommunicationsequipment and computers to all Eastern Bloc countries.andM;[] Dropping more than a third of the list of products banned form from exportto the eastern bloc.andM;[] Increased flexibility in treatment of Eastern countries that pledge to usetechnologies acquired from the West for civilian purposes onlyandM;[] An additional and &quot;considerable reduction&quot; in the number of articles ofwhich Cocom bans exports by the end of this year, limiting bans to equipmentof strategic interest.andM;(Steve Gold/19900609)</TEXT></DOC>